Azure DNS

Overview of DNS

If you would like to let's say try to liken it to our past metaphors you would think of DNS as a huge phonebook that knows how to use other phonebooks. In the olden days, you used phonebooks so you would know what the phone number of the room you are trying to contact is and that is how DNS basically works. Instead of doing all of the complicated stuff of finding the server and specific IP of the service or domain you are trying to access, DNS works in a way where you have your domain name like a website and it is associated to an IP address. That information is stored in the phonebook or a DNS server and yes it has a dedicated server because first of all you need somewhere to put that information cached and then you need someone to do the looking up for you. That is what is called a query.
But what is actually a domain name or a Fully Qualified Domain Name or FQDN for short? You might think it is the full address of a website you know like facebook.com and you would be correct. Facebook is the main name while the .com is the tag that is also associated with a load of other websites that has the same ending tag. There are also country tags like .uk or .us and they also have their own directory too. That is also why the more popular tags like .com have more expensive stuff because more people are using that and maybe because of caching and lookup purposes it takes up space in a DNS server.
There are two types of DNS servers however, authoritative and non-authoritative. The difference is that you can consider the authoritative as the master list that has the domain name and the associated IP address while the non-authoritative also has it but with a key difference. The data in it is cached meaning it is not originally from there but taken from a query to the authoritative server. But what if the master list decided to change a few things like the IP address associated to the domain name? That is where TTL comes into play. TTL means Time to Live, so whatever cached data you might have in your non-authoritative server it will get deleted and the same server will ask for the correct information this time.
Now you might be wondering, okay so what actually happens between me typing facebook.com and the page loading? Here is the basic flow of how a DNS query actually resolves. First your device checks its own local cache to see if it already knows the answer from a previous visit. If it does not find it there your device asks a DNS resolver, which is usually provided by your ISP or a service like Google's 8.8.8.8. The resolver then goes on a little journey on your behalf. It first asks a root server which does not know the answer but knows who to ask next. The root server points it toward the TLD server which handles the .com directory. The TLD server then points it to the authoritative server for facebook.com specifically. That authoritative server finally hands back the actual IP address. The resolver caches that answer for future use based on the TTL and sends it back to your device. Your device then connects to that IP and the page loads. All of that happens in milliseconds.
Now here is the part that should make you a little uncomfortable. By default all of that querying we just talked about happens in plain text. That means anyone sitting between you and your DNS resolver, your ISP, a bad actor on the same network, anyone really, can see every single domain name you are looking up. They cannot necessarily see the content of what you are doing but they can see that you visited facebook.com at 2am on a Tuesday and that is already a privacy problem.
That is where DNS over HTTPS or DoH comes in, and its sibling DNS over TLS or DoT. What these do is wrap your DNS queries inside an encrypted tunnel so that the same snooping we just described becomes much harder to pull off. Instead of your query going out in the open it goes through HTTPS just like when you visit a secure website. The contents are scrambled to anyone trying to intercept it. Most modern browsers now support DoH natively and services like Cloudflare's 1.1.1.1 and Google's 8.8.8.8 both support it as well. It is not a perfect solution because your resolver still knows what you are looking up, but it is significantly better than the default and worth enabling wherever you can.

DNS Records
Now that you know how DNS works as a concept, we need to talk about what actually lives inside that phonebook. Because a phonebook is only as useful as the entries written in it and DNS records are exactly those entries. Each record type serves a specific purpose and tells the DNS server something different about the domain it is responsible for.
The first and most important one you need to know is the A record. This is the most fundamental entry in the phonebook. It maps a domain name directly to an IPv4 address. So when you type facebook.com your DNS resolver is ultimately looking for an A record that says facebook.com lives at this specific IP address. This is the one you will be creating most often when you set up your own services in Azure.
The AAAA record is the same thing as an A record but for IPv6 addresses instead. The four As are not a typo, they represent the fact that IPv6 is four times the size of IPv4. You will see these less often in day to day work but they exist and now you know what they are.
The CNAME record or Canonical Name record is essentially an alias. Instead of pointing a domain name to an IP address it points one domain name to another domain name. So if you have www.facebook.com and you want it to go to the same place as facebook.com you would create a CNAME record that says www.facebook.com is just another name for facebook.com. Azure uses these a lot when you are mapping custom domains to Azure services because the underlying IP of an Azure service can change but the service hostname stays the same.
The MX record or Mail Exchange record is specifically for email. It tells the world which server is responsible for receiving email for a domain. So when someone sends an email to you at yourname@yourdomain.com the sending mail server looks up the MX record for yourdomain.com to figure out where to deliver it. If you ever set up a custom domain with Gmail or Microsoft 365 for business email this is the record you will be configuring.
The TXT record is a flexible record that can hold any text you want to associate with a domain. In practice it is used most often for domain verification and email security. When a service like Google or Microsoft wants to verify that you actually own a domain they will ask you to create a TXT record with a specific value they give you. Once they see that record in your DNS they know you have access to the domain settings and therefore own it.
The NS record or Name Server record tells the world which DNS servers are authoritative for your domain. Think of it as the phonebook entry that says if you want the real authoritative answers about this domain go ask these specific servers. When you register a domain and point it to Azure DNS for example, you update the NS records at your registrar to point to Azure's name servers.
The SOA record or Start of Authority record is automatically created whenever you set up a DNS zone and you generally do not touch it yourself. It contains administrative information about the zone like who is responsible for it and how often secondary DNS servers should check for updates. Think of it as the cover page of the phonebook.
One last thing worth knowing is that all of these records have a TTL value attached to them just like we discussed earlier. A shorter TTL means changes propagate faster but it also means more frequent queries hitting your DNS server. A longer TTL means less traffic but if you need to change something like an IP address it will take longer for the rest of the world to see the updated information. When you are planning a migration or a change to a critical service it is good practice to lower your TTL a day or two beforehand so the change takes effect faster when you are ready to make it.

